    "title": {
        "rendered": "MatR: Bruce Springsteen and USA For Africa: We Are the World"
    },
    "content": {
        "rendered": "<blockquote><p><span style=\"font-size: 14pt;\">&#8220;Anytime somebody asks you to take one night of your time to stop people starving to death&#8230; you can\u2019t say no.&#8221; &#8212; <em>Bruce Springsteen, January 28, 1985</em></span></p></blockquote>\n<p>In late November 1984, the biggest names in British and Irish popular music banded together in the studio to record &#8220;Do They Know It&#8217;s Christmas,&#8221; which became an instant smash hit and raised more than \u00a38 million for African famine relief in the song&#8217;s first year.</p>\n<p>The success of the Band Aid single immediately caught the attention of American musician and activist Harry Belafonte, who enlisted fundraiser Ken Kragen to make an American response record happen.</p>\n<p>Kragen and Belafonte spent that holiday season relentlessly recruiting. Michael Jackson and Lionel Richie signed on right away and offered to write the song. Kenny Rogers and Stevie Wonder signed on early, too. Quincy Jones agreed to produce the single, and gradually a line-up came together for a project called USA for Africa.</p>\n<p>Kragen had a dream &#8220;get,&#8221; though. He wanted the most popular rock star in the world: Bruce Springsteen, who at the time was in the middle of his marathon, mammoth Born in the U.S.A. Tour.</p>\n<p>Kragen implored Jon Landau to secure Bruce&#8217;s participation, but Landau set expectations low&#8211;not because Bruce wouldn&#8217;t want to participate, but because the logistics were challenging. The recording session was slated for the night of January 28, 1985 in Los Angeles, immediately following the live broadcast of the American Music Awards.</p>\n<p>Bruce was scheduled to end his current leg of the tour the night before in Syracuse, three thousand miles away. Getting across the country the next day for an all-night recording session was a lot to ask. Heck, Bruce was nominated for a few AMAs that night (and won one), and yet he didn&#8217;t even attend the ceremony.</p>\n<div id=\"v-GVzRSj7w-1\" class=\"video-player\"><iframe title='VideoPress Video Player' aria-label='VideoPress Video Player' width='758' height='504' src='https://videopress.com/embed/GVzRSj7w?hd=1&amp;cover=1&amp;loop=0&amp;autoPlay=0&amp;permalink=1&amp;muted=0&amp;controls=1&amp;playsinline=0&amp;useAverageColor=0&amp;preloadContent=metadata' frameborder='0' allowfullscreen data-resize-to-parent=\"true\" allow='clipboard-write'></iframe><script src='https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/plugins/video/assets/js/next/videopress-iframe.js'></script></div>\n<p>But a few weeks before the scheduled recording session, Landau called Kragen and told him that Bruce was on board. And once Bruce was on board, <em>everyone</em> was on board. A wave of artists signed up after Bruce, and on the morning of January 28th, Bruce got on a plane and flew across the country to Los Angeles.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/tSlsjEk8VgQ?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>There was no after-party at the AMAs that night; instead, the artists shuttled over to the studio in their limos or private cars. All except Bruce Springsteen, that is, who had just flown into town, rented a car for himself, drove to the studio, and exclaimed excitedly as he walked inside to <a href=\"https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2021/01/29/where-the-band-was-los-angeles-january-28-29-1985-clydes-story/\">all who could hear</a>, &#8220;I just got a great parking spot!&#8221;</p>\n<p>While the starstruck artists assembled and greeted each other (many had never met each other before), the song itself was still coming together. Jackson and Richie and only just completed writing it one week earlier to the day, and even as the artists were reading their music, they were making spot changes, like swapping in &#8220;better day&#8221; for &#8220;brighter day.&#8221; It was almost midnight, and they hadn&#8217;t yet begun to record.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/n4IIW_gQuic?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>When recording finally began, the sessions lasted all through the night, with the artists waiting patiently for their turn in the spotlight. Bruce nursed a beer while he waited, and at one point he absent-mindedly left it on a riser next to Michael Jackson, who playfully posed with it for a photo which ended up leaking to the press.</p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" data-attachment-id=\"32652\" data-permalink=\"https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2022/01/30/matr-bruce-springsteen-and-just-about-everyone-we-are-the-world/bossking/#main\" data-orig-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/bossking.png?fit=1196%2C836&amp;ssl=1\" data-orig-size=\"1196,836\" data-comments-opened=\"1\" data-image-meta=\"{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}\" data-image-title=\"bossking\" data-image-description=\"\" data-image-caption=\"\" data-medium-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/bossking.png?fit=300%2C210&amp;ssl=1\" data-large-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/bossking.png?fit=758%2C530&amp;ssl=1\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-32652\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/bossking.png?resize=758%2C531&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" width=\"758\" height=\"531\" srcset=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/bossking.png?resize=300%2C210&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/bossking.png?resize=1024%2C716&amp;ssl=1 1024w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/bossking.png?resize=768%2C537&amp;ssl=1 768w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/bossking.png?w=1196&amp;ssl=1 1196w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 758px) 100vw, 758px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" /></p>\n<p>While some artists recorded, others rehearsed. Bruce took his part seriously, rehearsing take after take, including lines that wouldn&#8217;t make it into the final version. Check out nine minutes of Bruce&#8217;s rehearsals below.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/a345Q_COly0?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>Bruce&#8217;s contributions were both memorable and spontaneous. He enters with thunder on the chorus, his trademark rasp filled with empathy, and as for that unforgettable duet with Stevie Wonder, that was divine on-the-fly inspiration.</p>\n<p>\u201cGod must have tapped me on the shoulder,&#8221; said Quincy Jones to <em>Rolling Stone, &#8220;</em>to save the record by suggesting that I ask Bruce Springsteen \u2014 for no logical reason at all \u2014 to supply solo answers to the choir melody on the title choruses because of the textures and intensity of his truly unique vocal equipment, especially in this register.\u201d But instead of trading off with the choir, Jones called Stevie back the next night to record duet vocals to pair with Bruce, and the composite result powered the song through its final moments.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/9AjkUyX0rVw?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>&#8220;We Are The World&#8221; ended up eclipsing the money made by &#8220;Do They Know It&#8217;s Christmas,&#8221; raising more than $63 million (in 1985 dollars) for humanitarian aid. It became the eighth-best-selling physical media single of all time and remains a touchpoint in pop culture history for anyone alive at the time.</p>\n<p>&#8220;We Are The World&#8221; featured the talents and contributions of dozens of artists and raised awareness and resources to fight hunger not just in Africa but in the U.S.A. as well. Bruce was just one of many who gave their time and talent that night, but without him the song wouldn&#8217;t have been the same.</p>\n<p><strong>We Are The World<br />\n</strong><strong>Recorded:\u00a0</strong>January 28-29, 1985<br />\n<strong>Released:\u00a0</strong><em>We Are The World</em> (1985)<br />\n<strong>Never performed live</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n",
        "protected": false
    },
    "excerpt": {
        "rendered": "<p>Bruce was just one of many who participated in the USA For Africa project, but his contributions provided some of the song&#8217;s most memorable moments.</p>\n",
        "protected": false
    },
